Paipo

'''Paipo''' boards as we apply the term include any prone-ridden surfcraft which aren't either inflatable mats or traditional finless soft bodyboards.

The original paipos were finless wooden boards developed in Hawaii. By the 60's the world of paipo had grown to include small foam/fiberglass bellyboards with surfboard fins. Both types still exist today although in very small numbers.

The use of a "Paipo" board is probably the oldest form of "board" surfing. It's recorded Captain Cook saw  the villagers riding them when he came to Hawaii in 1778. Those boards were about 3' to 6' and were ridden "prone" on the belly, or on the knees.

